					<p><b>Set Theory</b><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"> is a branch of =
mathematical logic where we learn sets and their properties. A set is a col=
lection of objects or groups of objects. These objects are often called ele=
ments or members of a set. For example, a group of players in a cricket tea=
m is a set.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Since the number of players in a crick=
et team could be only 11 at a time, thus we can say, this set is a finite s=
et. Another example of a finite set is a set of English vowels. But there a=
re many sets that have infinite members such as a set of natural numbers, a=
 set of whole numbers, set of real numbers, set of imaginary numbers, etc.&=
nbsp;</span></p>
<h2><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Set Theory Origin</span></h2>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Georg Cantor (1845-1918), a German mat=
hematician, initiated the concept =E2=80=98Theory of sets=E2=80=99 or =E2=
=80=98Set Theory=E2=80=99. While working on =E2=80=9C</span><i><span style=
=3D"font-weight: 400;">Problems on Trigonometric Series</span></i><span sty=
le=3D"font-weight: 400;">=E2=80=9D,&nbsp; he encountered sets, that have be=
come one of the most fundamental concepts in mathematics. Without understan=
ding sets, it will be difficult to explain the other concepts such as relat=
ions, functions, sequences, probability, geometry, etc.</span></p>
<h2>Definition of Sets</h2>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">As we have already learned in the intr=
oduction, set is a well-defined collection of objects or people. Sets can b=
e related to many real-life examples, such as the number of rivers in India=
, number of colours in a rainbow, etc.&nbsp;</span></p>
<h3>Example</h3>
<p>To understand sets, consider a practical scenario. While going to school=
 from home, Nivy decided to note down the names of restaurants which come i=
n between. The list of the restaurants, in the order they came, was:</p>
<p><span class=3D"latex-for-amp"></span></p><div class=3D"mathjax-scroll">\=
(\begin{array}{l} List\ 1: R_A ~~~~~&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R_=
B ~~~~~&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R_C ~~~~~&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbs=
p;&nbsp;&nbsp; R_D ~~~~~&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R_E \end{array=
} \)</div><p></p>
<p>The above-mentioned list is a collection of objects. Also, it is well-de=
fined. By well-defined, it is meant that anyone should be able to tell whet=
her the object belongs to the particular collection or not. E. g. a station=
ary shop can=E2=80=99t come in the category of the restaurants. If the coll=
ection of objects is well-defined, it is known as a set.</p>
<p>The objects in a set are referred to as elements of the set. A set can h=
ave finite or infinite elements. While coming back from the school, Nivy wa=
nted to confirm the list what she had made earlier. This time again, she wr=
ote the list in the order in which restaurants came. The new list was:</p>
<p><span class=3D"latex-for-amp"></span></p><div class=3D"mathjax-scroll">\=
(\begin{array}{l}List\ 2: R_E ~~~~~&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbs=
p; R_D~~~~~&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R_C ~~~~~&nbsp;&nbsp;=
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; R_B&nbsp;&nbsp;~~~~~&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;=
 R_A \end{array} \)</div><p></p>
<p>Now, this is a different list. But is a different set? The answer is no.=
 The order of elements has no significance in sets so it is still the same =
set.</p>
<h2>Representation of Sets</h2>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Sets can be represented in two ways:</=
span></p>
<ol>
<li><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Roster Form or Tabular form</span></l=
i>
<li><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Set Builder Form</span></li>
</ol>
<h3>Roster Form</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">In roster form, all the elements of th=
e set are listed, separated by commas and enclosed between curly braces { }=
.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Example: If set represents all the lea=
p years between the year 1995 and 2015, then it would be described using Ro=
ster form as:</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">A =3D{1996,2000,2004,2008,2012}</span>=
</p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Now, the elements inside the braces ar=
e written in ascending order. This could be descending order or any random =
order. As discussed before, the order doesn=E2=80=99t matter for a set repr=
esented in the Roster Form.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Also, multiplicity is ignored while re=
presenting the sets. E.g. If <strong>L</strong> represents a set that conta=
ins all the letters in the word ADDRESS, the proper Roster form representat=
ion would be</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">L =3D{A,D,R,E,S }=3D {S,E,D,A,R}&nbsp;=
&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">L=E2=89=A0 {A,D,D,R,E,S,S}</span></p>
<h3>Set Builder Form</h3>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">In set builder form, all the elements =
have a common property. This property is not applicable to the objects that=
 do not belong to the set.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Example: If set </span><b>S</b><span s=
tyle=3D"font-weight: 400;"> has all the elements which are even prime numbe=
rs, it is represented as:</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">S=3D{ x: x is an even prime number}</s=
pan></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">where =E2=80=98x=E2=80=99 is a symboli=
c representation that is used to describe the element.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">=E2=80=98:=E2=80=99 means =E2=80=98suc=
h that=E2=80=99</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">=E2=80=98{}=E2=80=99 means =E2=80=98th=
e set of all=E2=80=99</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">So, S =3D { x:x is an even prime numbe=
r } is read as =E2=80=98the set of all x such that x is an even prime numbe=
r=E2=80=99. The roster form for this set S would be S =3D 2. This set conta=
ins only one element. Such sets are called singleton/unit sets.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Another Example:</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">F =3D {p: p is a set of two-digit perf=
ect square numbers}</span></p>
<p><b>How?</b></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">F =3D {16, 25, 36, 49, 64, 81}</span><=
/p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">We can see, in the above example, 16 i=
s a square of 4, 25 is square of 5, 36 is square of 6, 49 is square of 7, 6=
4 is square of 8 and 81 is a square of 9}.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Even though, 4, 9, 121, etc., are also=
 perfect squares, but they are not elements of the set F, because the it is=
 limited to only two-digit perfect square.</span></p>
<h2>Types of Sets</h2>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">The sets are further categorised into =
different types, based on elements or types of elements. These different ty=
pes of sets in basic set theory are:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Finite set: The number of elements is finite</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Infinite set: The number of elements are infinite</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Empty set: It has no elements</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Singleton set: It has one only element</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Equal set: Two sets are equal if they have same elements</span></li=
>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Equivalent set: Two sets are equivalent if they have same number of=
 elements</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Power set: A set of every possible subset.</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Universal set: Any set that contains all the sets under considerati=
on.</span></li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><span style=3D"font-weight=
: 400;">Subset: When all the elements of set A belong to set B, then A is s=
ubset of B</span></li>
</ul>
<h2>Set Theory Symbols</h2>
<p>There are several symbols that are adopted for common sets. They are giv=
en in the table below:</p>
<p>Table 1: Symbols denoting common sets</p>
<table class=3D"table-bordered">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td style=3D"text-align: center;" width=3D"69">Symbol</td>
<td style=3D"text-align: center;" width=3D"562"><strong>Corresponding Set</=
strong></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td width=3D"69">&nbsp;N</td>
<td width=3D"562">Represents the set of all Natural numbers i.e. all the po=
sitive integers.<p></p>
<p>This can also be represented by Z<sup>+</sup>.</p>
<p>Examples: 9, 13, 906, 607, etc.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td width=3D"69">&nbsp;Z</td>
<td width=3D"562">Represents the set of all integers<p></p>
<p>The symbol is derived from the German word <em>Zahl</em>, which means nu=
mber.</p>
<p>Positive and negative integers are denoted by Z<sup>+</sup>&nbsp;and Z<s=
up>=E2=80=93</sup> respectively.</p>
<p>Examples: -12, 0, 23045, etc.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td width=3D"69">&nbsp;Q</td>
<td width=3D"562">Represents the set of Rational numbers<p></p>
<p>The symbol is derived from the word <em>Quotient</em>. It is defined as =
the quotient of two integers (with non-zero denominator)</p>
<p>Positive and negative rational numbers are denoted by Q<sup>+</sup> and =
Q<sup>=E2=80=93</sup>&nbsp;respectively.</p>
<p>Examples: 13/9. -6/7, 14/3, etc.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td width=3D"69">&nbsp;R</td>
<td width=3D"562">Represents the Real numbers i.e. all the numbers located =
on the number line.<p></p>
<p>Positive and negative real numbers are denoted by R<sup>+</sup> and R<su=
p>=E2=80=93</sup>&nbsp;respectively.</p>
<p>Examples: 4.3, =CF=80, 4=E2=88=9A 3, etc.</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td width=3D"69">&nbsp;C</td>
<td width=3D"562">Represents the set of Complex numbers.<p></p>
<p>Examples: 4 + 3i, i, etc.</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h3>Other Notations</h3>
<table class=3D"table-bordered">
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><b>Symbol</b></td>
<td><b>Symbol Name</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">{ }</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">set</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">A =E2=88=AA B</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">A union B</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">A =E2=88=A9 B</span></td>
<td><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">A intersection B</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
